Commonshub Onboarding Flow — Frontend/Backend Handshake Spec (v0.1)

1) Goal

Provide a frictionless creator onboarding flow that:
	•	produces a complete Phase A Blueprint (copy-and-save, no purchase required)
	•	generates a resume link token only after Phase A completion
	•	then hands off to product UI for plan selection + provisioning (Phase B)

Core principle: Phase A is identity configuration; Phase B is infrastructure. Resume uses stored state; the model is not invoked on resume.
⸻

2) Entities (backend source of truth)

Blueprint (authoritative config object)

Created early, becomes immutable after Phase A commit except for lifecycle transitions.

Fields (minimum for provisioning & dashboard):
	•	blueprint_id (uuid)
	•	admin_email
	•	positioning
	•	community_name
	•	instance_slug
	•	domain_path (enum string: commonshub_subdomain | external_subdomain | custom_domain)
	•	domain_candidate (nullable; required for external/custom)
	•	resolved_domain (nullable until locked)
	•	short_description
	•	header_line
	•	owner_username (required for Phase A completion)
	•	owner_bio
	•	long_description (generated at commit)
	•	welcome_announcement (generated at commit)
	•	visual_asset_direction (generated at commit)
	•	launch_mode (pilot|flagship)
	•	lifecycle_state (draft|phase_a_complete|purchased|provisioning|live)
	•	timestamps: blueprint_created_at, phase_a_completed_at

Important: provisioning consumes owner_username + resolved_domain (or domain_candidate depending on infra). owner_handle is display-only and can be derived.

Session / Transcript (non-user-facing)
	•	session_id
	•	blueprint_id
	•	diagnostic_transcript (step-by-step options shown, recommendation, choice, iterations)
	•	outcome (proceeded_to_setup, abandonment_reason, acceptance metrics)


	Resume Token (auth + routing)
	•	resume_link_token (one-time / rotated on use)
	•	blueprint_id
	•	session_id
	•	expires_at
	•	revoked_at (nullable)

⸻

2B) Generated Artifacts (always produced)

Every completed Phase A session produces three separate persisted artifacts.

These serve different systems and must never be merged.

⸻

1) Blueprint JSON (authoritative configuration)

Purpose:
Provisioning, dashboard rendering, resume state.

Source of truth for infrastructure.

Contains:
	•	Only final locked values
	•	Generated identity text blocks
	•	Lifecycle + timestamps
	•	Fields required to create the instance

Never contains:
	•	options
	•	recommendations
	•	user iteration history
	•	analytics

Already defined in section 2 — no change to structure.

⸻

2) Diagnostic Transcript (flow tuning artifact)

Purpose:
	•	option quality analysis
	•	model tuning
	•	UX debugging
	•	demo forensics

This is the full decision surface.

This is not a chat log.
It is structured step telemetry.

Structure (JSON)

diagnostic_transcript {
  session_id
  blueprint_id
  phase_reached: "A" | "B"

  steps: [
    {
      step_id
      step_header
      iteration_index

      options_presented: [
        { label, text }
      ]

      recommended_option_label
      recommended_value
      recommendation_reason

      creator_choice {
        choice_type
        chosen_option_label
        chosen_value
        refinement_notes
      }

      final_value_locked: boolean
      locked_value

      recommendation_followed: true | false | null
    }
  ]
}

Critical rule
Every regeneration of a step = new step record
(same step_id, higher iteration_index).

This prevents the “model ran past my decision” bug.

⸻

3) Outcome / Stats Artifact (analytics artifact)

Purpose:
	•	funnel measurement
	•	onboarding optimization
	•	segmentation
	•	follow-up automation

This is computed, not generated by the model.

Structure

outcome {
  blueprint_id
  session_id

  phase_completed: "A" | "B" | null
  proceeded_to_setup: boolean
  abandonment_reason: string | null

  recommendation_acceptance_rate
  custom_name_used
  iteration_count_total

  time_to_blueprint_minutes
  time_to_provision_minutes (Phase B only)
}

Computation source
These values are derived only from the diagnostic transcript
→ never from the Blueprint.

⸻

2C) Persistence timing

At Phase A commit

Backend must atomically:
	1.	Save Blueprint JSON
	2.	Save Diagnostic Transcript
	3.	Compute and save Outcome artifact
	4.	Generate resume token
	5.	Send resume email
	6.	Token rotation rule: whenever a resume link is successfully used, issue a new token and invalidate the previous token.

⸻

2D) Storage model (recommended)

Three tables / collections:

blueprints
diagnostic_transcripts
outcomes

Linked by:

blueprint_id
session_id

2E) Retrieval responsibility

Provisioning service reads:

Blueprint only

Dashboard reads:

Blueprint only

Internal admin / tuning tools read:

Diagnostic Transcript + Outcome

Creator never sees:

Diagnostic Transcript
Outcome artifact





3) Phase boundaries

Phase A — Pre-Commit Blueprint
	•	No purchase
	•	No provisioning
	•	Produces final Blueprint JSON + resume token
	•	Deterministic and resumable

Phase B — Provisioning & Launch
	•	Starts only after purchase success
	•	Provisions Mastodon instance and returns admin deep links + dashboard

⸻

4) Frontend state machine (what FE renders)

Resume Path (magic link)

If the product UI loads /resume?token=... :
	•	FE calls GET /v1/onboarding/resume/{token}
	•	FE does not invoke the model
	•	FE routes based on next_state:
		- plan_select → show Plan Select screen
		- provisioning_status → show Provisioning Status screen
		- dashboard → show Dashboard
		- invalid → start New Session Path (Step 0B)

Step 0B — Admin email

FE collects email and calls backend to create draft blueprint.

Step 0C — Micro-intake

FE collects focus + optional links (stored in transcript/session; focus may be persisted in blueprint if useful).

Steps 1–5 — Decision steps

Each step is “options → recommendation → user choice.”
Hard rule: if user response isn’t explicit approval/selection, FE must stay on same step and request new options from model/service.

Phase A Commit Moment (after Step 5 approval)

Backend:
	1.	persists blueprint fields
	2.	generates long_description + welcome_announcement + visual_asset_direction
	3.	sets lifecycle_state = phase_a_complete
	4.	generates resume token
	5.	sends resume email
	6.	returns blueprint summary payload to FE

FE:
	•	displays Blueprint Summary block
	•	then asks “Ready to proceed to setup?”

If proceed → FE exits onboarding to Plan Select screen (handled by product UI).
If pause → FE asks exactly one abandonment reason prompt then ends.

⸻

5) Backend endpoints (proposed minimal API)

A) Session + Blueprint draft

POST /v1/onboarding/sessions
Request:
	•	admin_email
Response:
	•	session_id
	•	blueprint_id
	•	lifecycle_state: draft

B) Save micro-intake

POST /v1/onboarding/sessions/{session_id}/intake
Request:
	•	focus (required)
	•	links (optional array)
Response:
	•	ok

C) Get step options (the “model output” boundary)

POST /v1/onboarding/sessions/{session_id}/steps/{step_id}:generate
Request:
	•	iteration_index
	•	prior_choice (nullable)
Response:
	•	step_id
	•	step_header
	•	options[] (label + text)
	•	recommended_option_label
	•	recommendation_reason

(This can be implemented as a backend “orchestrator” that calls the model and stores transcript.)

D) Submit choice / approval

POST /v1/onboarding/sessions/{session_id}/steps/{step_id}:choose
Request:
	•	choice_type = approve_recommendation | choose_option | custom_choice | more_options | refine_direction | reject_all
	•	chosen_option_label (nullable)
	•	chosen_value (nullable)
	•	refinement_notes (nullable)
Response:
	•	advance_allowed: boolean
	•	if advance_allowed: locked_value (verbatim)
	•	if not: next_action = regenerate

Backend logic determines if it counts as explicit approval.

E) Commit Phase A

POST /v1/onboarding/sessions/{session_id}:commit_phase_a
Precondition:
	•	Step 1–5 locked
	•	owner_username present
Behavior:
	•	generates derived text blocks
	•	sets phase_a_completed_at
	•	sets lifecycle_state phase_a_complete
	•	generates resume_link_token
	•	sends email
Response:
	•	blueprint_json
	•	blueprint_summary_render_data
	•	resume_link_token (optional to return; email is primary)

F) Resume by token (UI routing)

GET /v1/onboarding/resume/{resume_link_token}

Behavior:
	•	validate token (not expired, not revoked)
	•	rotate token on success (issue new token, invalidate old)
	•	load blueprint + session state
	•	return next_state without running onboarding steps
Rules:
	•	if phase_completed != "A" → next_state = invalid
	•	if phase_completed == "A" and purchase_success != true → next_state = plan_select
	•	if purchase_success == true and provisioning_complete != true → next_state = provisioning_status
	•	if provisioning_complete == true → next_state = dashboard

Response:
	•	blueprint_id
	•	next_state = plan_select | provisioning_status | dashboard | invalid
	•	optional deep links

Internal Artifact Retrieval

Get outcome (internal, not exposed to creators)

	GET /v1/onboarding/sessions/{session_id}/outcome

Get diagnostic transcript (internal, , not exposed to creators)

	GET /v1/onboarding/sessions/{session_id}/diagnostic


⸻

6) Determinism rules (prevents “ran past my decision” bugs)
	1.	Any value shown as Locked: must be persisted verbatim and never regenerated.
	2.	Phase A completion is invalid if owner_username missing.
	3.	domain_path stored as an enum string, not “Option A/B/C”.
	4.	After Phase A commit, the only transitions are lifecycle transitions (purchased/provisioning/live). No content regeneration.
	5.	Resume never reruns Phase A steps; it only routes based on persisted state.

⸻

7) Domain resolution notes
	•	For Commonshub subdomain: backend constructs resolved_domain = {instance_slug}.commonshub.social
	•	For external/custom: domain_candidate locked first; resolved_domain becomes live after DNS verification/provisioning (depending on infra)

FE should treat resolved_domain as the display authority when present, otherwise show domain_candidate.

⸻

8) Provisioning handshake (Phase B)

On purchase success:
POST /v1/provisioning/jobs
Request:
	•	blueprint_id
Response:
	•	job_id, status

Provisioner reads Blueprint JSON only (no transcript), sets up instance, then updates:
	•	lifecycle_state provisioning → live
	•	admin URLs + credentials delivery mechanism
